==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infuriate
<hw>In*fu"ri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[It.
<ets>infuriato</ets>, p. p. of <ets>infuriare</ets>. See
<er>Infuriate</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>Enraged; raging;
furiously angry; infuriated.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inflamed beyond the most <qex>infuriate</qex> wrath.</q>
<rj><qau>Thomson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infuriate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infuriate
<hw>In*fu"ri*ate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Infuriated</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Infuriating</conjf>]</vmorph> <ety>[It.
<ets>infuriato</ets>, p. p. of <ets>infuriare</ets>; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>furia</ets> fury, L.
<ets>furia</ets>. See <er>Fury</er>.]</ety> <def>To render furious; to
enrage; to exasperate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those curls of entangled snakes with which Erinys is said to have
<qex>infuriated</qex> Athemas and Ino.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H.
More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infuriated</ent>⟦br⟧
